<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-044-178  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 044 178.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>InfoWorld  Jan 15 1990 v12 n3 p49(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Year of the LAN. (local area network) (Perspectives)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Stephens, Mark.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Many observers expect local-area network (LAN) use to growexponentially in 1990, and LANs are virtually certain to becomewidespread in the 1990s.andP;  Eight important developments in 1989will determine the future of networking, according to LANadministrators: IBM's endorsement of Ethernet signified itsinterest in multivendor environments; Compaq's entry into thenetworking business with its Systempro line of file servers gavenetworking a major boost; the introduction of the 10-Base-Tstandard for connecting Ethernet LANs over telephone wiring hasenabled many users to network their facilities at low cost;network management standards and protocols became real products in1989; a new class of 'super servers' emerged; SQL-typeapplications servers made LANs vital to many corporations; LANManager was integrated with LAN Server; and Novell's NetWare 386simplified networking for many users.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     ForecastingTrendsLocal Area NetworksMicrocomputersReview of Past Year.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   The year of the LAN? (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>